You missed the left thumb and you might also want to change the color of the finger nails.

Also I'd like to quote myself for some general advice with editing skin:

You don't recolor for the best results.
What you should do it select roughly the are you want to change leaving a bit of margin around it but not too much, then making it into a new layer via copy.
Once you have your new layer you take some kind of reference drawing with nice looking human skin in it, select an area that contains a proportional amount of all the skins different shades and make it into a new layer via cut.
Now you use match colour to match your cut sampled layer to your copied destination layer.
Your margin will inevitably look weird but that'd why you then erase it manually, making sure to set your erasers opacity to around 60% to get a nice smooth looking edge (multiple passes will be required though).

If you're dealing with a character with multiple fur colors, make each fur color it's own copied layer matching each separately, the edges will inevitably look weird or be mismatched so use either a brush with a colour sampled from the surrounding area or the clone stamp tool if there's texture with their hardness and opacity turned way down (around 20% opacity and 40% hardness). Your going to have to do a fuck ton of passes to build up the colour but the results will be much smoother. Make sure to regularly re sample from the area your working in to maintain consistency and to achieve good color blending.

All of this should be done after you've full redrawn the image to get rid of fur, claws, muzzles, digit grade feet and so on.

Anyway that's how I do it, pic related is an example.
